SIMPLE: grid
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Grid
<hw>Grid</hw> <pr>(gr⟦icr⟧d)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A
grating of thin parallel bars, similar to a gridiron.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Elec.)</fld> <def>A plate or sheet of lead with
perforations, or other irregularities of surface, by which the active
material of a secondary battery or accumulator is supported.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Electronics)</fld> <def>a mesh or coil of fine wire
in an electron tube, connected to the circuit so as to regulate the
current passing through the tube.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>any network of crossing horizontal and vertical
lines; -- they are used, for example, as reference coordinates to locate
objects or places on a map.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>anything resembling a grid{4}, as the Manhattan
street <ex>grid</ex>. See also <er>gridlock</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>a network of connected conductors for distributing
electrical power, especially one using high-tension lines for wide
geographic distribution of power; <as>as, the Northeast power
<ex>grid</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <fld>(Football)</fld> <def>the
<er>gridiron</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Griddle</ent>⟦br⟧
